vectorData.altText: 5. Blood brain barrier breakdown occurs in which pathology / pathologies? Choose all that apply.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
That’s right!  BBB breakdown occurs in tumour, inflammation and arteriovenous malformation. BBB breakdown occurs in later stages of stroke, but not in the acute phase.

BBB breakdown results in increased permeability of brain capillaries. This causes vasogenic edema, in which fluid derived from plasma crosses the abnormally leaky vessel walls and accumulates in the interstitial space of the brain parenchyma. The excess fluid causes an increase in intracranial pressure, ICP, and can act like a space occupying lesion, compressing adjacent brain tissue.
In imaging, BBB breakdown can be seen with a contrast agent. A contrast agent gives a high signal in brain imaging. It can be given intravenously, and flows through the vascular system as images of the brain are taken. Contrast agent does not cross the intact BBB, and therefore does not enter the brain parenchyma in normal brains. With BBB breakdown, however, a contrast agent crosses the leaky vessel walls and bathes the adjacent brain parenchyma, giving a high signal in the region of BBB breakdown. A contrast agent commonly used in MRI is gadolinium.
BBB breakdown occurs in tumors, arteriovenous malformations and in inflammation. Inflammation occurs in multiple sclerosis, for instance, and in the later stages of stroke.

Gadolinium-enhanced MRI showing BBB breakdown in a glioblastoma multiforme.
Gadolinium-enhanced MRI showing BBB breakdown due to inflammation in active MS lesions.
